PREAMBLE

This Aethelgrad Reciprocal Public Code Covenant (the "Covenant") is a legal agreement between the copyright holder identified in the copyright notice above ("Licensor") and any individual or legal entity that downloads, clones, installs, executes, or distributes the Work ("Recipient").

This Covenant is a source‑available license. It is not submitted for OSI approval, and OSI definitions do not govern its interpretation. Publication of the Work does not constitute dedication to the public domain or any implied license beyond what this Covenant expressly grants.

For individuals, hobbyists, academics, and small entities (annual revenue < $100,000 USD), this license is perpetual, royalty‑free, and cannot be revoked except for material breach.
For commercial entities above that threshold, this license operates as a 40‑day evaluation period, after which a paid commercial license is required.

By obtaining a copy of the Work, the Recipient agrees to be bound by all terms and conditions of this Covenant.

ARTICLE 1: DEFINITIONS

1.1 "Work" means the software source code, object code, documentation, configuration files, build scripts, metadata, visual design elements (excluding generic colors or layout ideas), ASCII art, and any associated materials made available by the Licensor in any repository referencing this Covenant, together with all updates and successor versions.

1.2 "Recipient" means any individual or legal entity that downloads, clones, installs, executes, distributes, or otherwise obtains a copy of the Work. "Recipient" includes any parent company, subsidiary, affiliate, successor entity, or any entity under common ownership or control exceeding fifty percent (50%). For purposes of this definition, ownership of less than 50% does not create attribution of revenue or liability between entities. Moreover, portfolio companies of a venture capital firm are not considered affiliates of each other solely by virtue of common investment, unless there is actual shared management, joint control, or product integration.

1.3 "Derivative Work" means any work that contains, translates, modifies, or is otherwise based upon the Work in a manner that incorporates a substantial portion of the original expression, as determined under copyright law. Derivative Work includes code that, after normalizing variable names, whitespace, and comments, maintains substantially similar structural and logical organization as the Work. This determination may be supported by expert analysis including structural code comparison tools. Independent re‑implementation of functional ideas, algorithms, or patterns – without copying literal code or non‑literal protected structure – does not constitute a Derivative Work. A Recipient who has accessed the Work and subsequently creates a substantially similar implementation must, upon the Licensor’s request, provide a written declaration describing the independent development process, including a statement that no code from the Work was copied or translated. Failure to provide such declaration within 30 days creates a rebuttable presumption of copying.

1.4 "Contribution" means any code, documentation, or other material intentionally submitted to the Licensor for inclusion in the Work, excluding ephemeral communications (e.g., chat messages, issue comments) unless explicitly marked as a contribution. Submissions through pull requests, email attachments, or designated contribution channels are included.

1.5 "Licensor" means the individual or legal entity identified in the copyright notice accompanying this Work, together with its successors and assigns.

1.6 "Annual Revenue" means the gross revenue (USD equivalent) of the Recipient’s entire legal entity or, if the Recipient is a subsidiary, the gross revenue of the ultimate parent entity, as reported in the most recent fiscal year according to GAAP or IFRS, as applicable. For private entities that do not publicly report revenue, the Recipient may, at the Licensor’s option, either provide a certified statement of Annual Revenue signed under penalty of perjury by an officer or authorized owner, or consent to a review of relevant revenue records conducted by a mutually agreed independent certified public accountant under strict confidentiality. Revenue thresholds are adjusted annually for inflation based on the US Consumer Price Index. For revenue determination, the Licensor may consider publicly available corporate ownership records. If revenue is underreported due to offshore subsidiaries, the Licensor may request a certified revenue statement from the ultimate parent entity.

1.7 "Commercial Entity" means:
    (a) any Recipient with Annual Revenue exceeding $100,000 USD;
    (b) any entity that has received institutional venture capital funding, angel investment, venture debt, bridge loans, secondary market investments, or funding via convertible debt or Simple Agreements for Future Equity (SAFEs) exceeding $1,000,000 USD in aggregate;
    (c) any entity publicly traded on a securities exchange;
    (d) any government agency, public school, or state-owned enterprise with an annual operating budget or public funding allocation exceeding $10,000,000 USD; or
    (e) any registered non-profit organization or charity with an annual operating budget exceeding $5,000,000 USD.
    Closed rounds of equity financing, angel investments, convertible notes, and SAFEs all count toward the aggregate funding threshold under Section 1.7(b). Notwithstanding the foregoing, use of the Work by public schools, universities, and registered non-profit organizations for purely educational, academic, or humanitarian purposes – without commercial integration, monetization, or paid distribution – does not trigger Commercial Entity status regardless of operating budget.

1.8 The singular includes the plural, and "including" means "including without limitation".

1.9 "Developer Seat" means any individual human developer, software engineer, architect, or contractor who, on behalf of the Recipient, directly modifies the source code of the Work, compiles software incorporating the Work, or actively maintains a software application that integrates or links to the Work. "Developer Seat" also includes autonomous developer agents, automated cron scripts running in terminal shells executing CRUD or code generation pipelines, and containerized AI instances. Automated build servers, continuous integration/continuous deployment (CI/CD) pipelines, and deployment container nodes do not require Developer Seats unless they actively execute generative code modifications or autonomous deployments.

ARTICLE 2: COPYRIGHT LICENSE – SOVEREIGN RECIPROCAL DEVELOPER FRANCHISE

2.1 Grant for Non‑Commercial and Small Entities (The "Sovereign Reciprocal Developer Franchise").
Any Recipient that is not a Commercial Entity (as defined in Section 1.7) is granted a perpetual, irrevocable (except for breach of conditions), worldwide, non‑exclusive, royalty‑free, non‑transferable copyright license to:

    (a) reproduce, copy, and distribute the Work, in whole or in part, in source or object form;

    (b) prepare, use, and distribute Derivative Works;

    (c) publicly display, publicly perform, and otherwise use the Work; and

    (d) sublicense any of the foregoing rights to third parties, provided that no such sublicense shall grant broader rights than the sublicensee would otherwise be entitled to under this Covenant. If the sublicensee is a Commercial Entity, they remain fully subject to the commercial licensing requirements under Article 3. Any sublicense must include a copy of this Covenant and notice that the sublicense is conditional on the sublicensee’s own compliance.

This license cannot be revoked for arbitrary reasons; it may only be terminated for material breach of Articles 4, 5, or 10, with a 30‑day cure period.

2.2 Grant for Evaluation by Commercial Entities (The "Finite Commercial Evaluation Franchise").
Any Commercial Entity is granted a limited, royalty‑free, non‑transferable evaluation license to use the Work for a period of forty (40) calendar days from the date of first download, installation, or cloning (the "Evaluation Period"). During this period, the Commercial Entity may internally test, benchmark, and assess the Work for potential integration.

2.3 Post‑Evaluation Requirement.
Continued use of the Work by a Commercial Entity beyond the 40‑day Evaluation Period is strictly prohibited without a signed Commercial License Agreement from the Licensor. Continued use without an agreement constitutes willful copyright infringement and triggers the remedies in Article 7.

2.4 Patent License.
Each Contributor grants each Recipient a worldwide, non‑exclusive, royalty‑free patent license to make, use, sell, offer for sale, and import the Work, limited to patent claims necessarily infringed by that Contributor’s Contribution(s). If a Recipient files a patent infringement lawsuit against the Licensor or any Contributor alleging that the Work infringes a patent, all patent licenses granted under this Covenant terminate immediately.

2.5 No Implied Licenses.
No rights are granted by implication, estoppel, or otherwise beyond those expressly stated.

ARTICLE 3: REVENUE TIERS FOR COMMERCIAL LICENSES

This article applies only to Commercial Entities that have obtained a paid Commercial License Agreement. The terms below are the standard offer; the Licensor may negotiate different terms.

3.1 Standard Commercial Tiers.
The Licensor offers commercial licenses at the following annual rates (per developer seat):
Tier	Annual Revenue of Entity	Annual Fee per Seat
Startup	100k–10M	$600
Mid‑Market	10M–100M	$1,200
Enterprise	100M–1B	$2,400
Mega	Over $1B	$4,800

3.2 Minimum Fee.
The minimum annual commercial license fee is $1,200 total, regardless of seat count.

3.3 Tier Migration.
If an entity’s revenue moves between tiers, the new fee applies at the next renewal. No retroactive adjustment.

3.4 Retroactive Compliance for Unauthorized Distribution (The "Retroactive Compliance and Infringement Rectification Franchise" Clause).
Any Recipient who has distributed, sold, or otherwise commercially exploited the Work without prior authorization (including but not limited to digital marketplace partners, third-party distribution platforms, software registries, or plugin developers) may petition the Licensor for a Retroactive Compliance Agreement. The Licensor may, in its sole discretion, offer terms based on the Recipient's total infringing revenue as follows:

Infringing Revenue (USD)	Licensor's Share	Recipient Retains	Payment Terms
0–500	25%	75%	Single payment within 30 days
501–2,500	35%	65%	Single payment within 60 days
2,501–10,000	45%	55%	Up to 3 installments over 90 days
10,001–50,000	50%	50%	Up to 6 installments over 180 days
Over $50,000	50%	50%	Negotiated payment plan

The Licensor may, at their discretion, reduce the share by up to 50% for first-time offenders who:

    (a) provide full written disclosure of all infringing revenue, including screenshots, sales data, and platform analytics;

    (b) issue a public acknowledgment of the original authorship in the infringing product's description, on the distribution platform page, and in all relevant social media channels, reading:

    "This product incorporates code from [WORK], developed by [LICENSOR] under the ARPCC v2.5 license. The original author has graciously allowed continued use under these terms."

    (c) add a prominent link to the original repository;

    (d) remove all Protected Marks and any confusingly similar branding from the infringing product.

No Minimum Payment Floor. If the Recipient's total infringing revenue is zero, the Licensor may accept a written apology and public acknowledgment in lieu of payment.

Audit Rights. The Licensor may demand access to sales records, distribution dashboard analytics, and financial accounts to verify reported revenue. Refusal constitutes willful infringement and triggers Article 7 (Reasonable Damages) and Article 8 (Public Disclosure).

Repeat Offenders. Any Recipient who has previously benefited from this clause and is found to have committed a second violation shall be ineligible for any reduced share. The Licensor may pursue maximum damages under Article 7 without further notice.

This clause is not a right. It is a privilege. The Licensor may deny any request for any reason, or for no reason at all. Acceptance of this clause constitutes an admission of past infringement and waives any statute of limitations defenses for the period of infringement.

3.5 The "Equitable Hardship Mitigation and Non-Monetary Restitution Safe Harbor" Provision.
Notwithstanding Section 3.4, if the Recipient demonstrates genuine financial hardship (defined as total infringing revenue under $2,500 and verifiable inability to pay the calculated share), the Licensor may, in their sole discretion, accept one of the following in lieu of monetary payment:

    (a) A public video statement (minimum 30 seconds) in which the Recipient's authorized representative clearly, audibly, and in good faith acknowledges the infringement and endorses the original Work, posted to all public distribution platforms where the infringing product was marketed;

    (b) A written article or blog post (minimum 300 words) explaining in good faith what was copied, how it violated this Covenant, and linking to the original Work;

    (c) A contribution of code, documentation, or testing services to the original Work, of equivalent value as determined by the Licensor.

This provision exists to educate, not to destroy. The Licensor reserves the right to publish the terms of any such agreement as an example to other potential violators.

3.6 Central European Compliance (Poland & Germany).
For Recipients whose habitual residence or principal place of business is in the Republic of Poland or the Federal Republic of Germany, the following specific provisions apply:

    (a) Polish Copyright Act. The Licensor invokes the protection of the Polish Act on Copyright and Related Rights (Journal of Laws 2021, item 1062). Any violation of this Covenant shall entitle the Licensor to claim statutory damages under Article 79(1)(3) of that Act, which is limited to two (2) times the license fee that would have been owed (or up to three (3) times in the case of willful commercial infringement by a Commercial Entity), or three times (3x) the Base Rate under Article 7.2, at the Licensor's election. However, if the Recipient is a natural person (individual) or non-commercial entity who cooperates in good faith under Section 3.4, the statutory damages shall be capped at a maximum of five hundred Polish Złoty (500 PLN), or waived entirely in favor of a written apology and public acknowledgment under Section 3.5. The 500 PLN cap is adjusted annually for inflation based on the official Eurostat/GUS Consumer Price Index. The 500 PLN cap is lifted, and standard statutory or liquidated damages under Article 7 shall apply, if the Recipient acts in bad faith, ignores a written notice of non-compliance, or actively attempts to misrepresent original authorship or pass off the Work as their own. This ensures Polish hobbyists are protected from financial ruin while maintaining accountability.

    (b) German Copyright Act (UrhG). The 40‑day evaluation period in Article 2.2 constitutes a "test version" (Probeversion) within the meaning of German case law (BGH I ZR 3/08). Any use beyond that period without a paid license is an infringement under §97 UrhG, entitling the Licensor to injunctive relief and damages.

    (c) GDPR‑Compliant Audit. Any audit under Article 7.4 shall, for natural persons in the EU, be limited to financial records directly attributable to revenue generated by the Work. The auditor shall be an independent, certified accountant bound by professional secrecy. The Recipient may redact any personal data unrelated to the Work's revenue.

3.7 Startup Discount.
Notwithstanding Section 3.1, for Commercial Entities that are under three (3) years old from their date of incorporation or initial formation and have an Annual Revenue of under $5,000,000 USD, a Startup Discount is available: the Recipient may pay a reduced rate of $300 USD per Developer Seat per year for the first two (2) years of their paid Commercial License Agreement.

    (d) Public Disclosure Limitation. For natural persons (individuals) residing in the EU, the Licensor may not publish their name under Article 8 without a final court judgment of infringement. For legal entities (companies), the Licensor may publish the entity's name upon reasonable evidence of violation, without prior court order.

    (e) Clickwrap Enforceability. The Recipient's act of downloading, cloning, or installing the Work constitutes a clear declaration of intent (oświadczenie woli) under Polish Civil Code Art. 60 and is fully enforceable under German contract law.

ARTICLE 4: CONDITIONS AND LIMITATIONS

4.1 Preservation of Notices.
Any distribution of the Work or Derivative Work must retain all copyright, patent, trademark, and attribution notices from the original Work. All uncompiled inline software comments, license sync tokens, and architectural annotations are protected trade secrets under global trade secret laws and must not be altered, minified, or stripped.

4.2 Trademark Restrictions – The Core Brand Integrity and Anti-Dilution Shield.
Recipient may not use any trademark, service mark, trade name, logo, or brand identifier of the Licensor (including the Protected Marks listed in the Copyright Notice and any distinctive ASCII art layout headers or repository visual structures) without the Licensor’s express written permission. This prohibition does not apply to:

    (a) Nominative fair use to describe compatibility (e.g., "Compatible with [Work]");

    (b) Critical commentary or review;

    (c) Forks or Derivative Works that completely rebrand (see Section 4.3).

4.3 Absolute De‑Branding Requirement for Forks.
Any Recipient that creates a Derivative Work, fork, or alternative distribution must change all names, logos, and branding to be clearly distinct. The name may not include the Licensor’s Protected Marks, nor any variant such as [Original]-fork, free-[Original], or open-[Original]. GitHub’s automatic fork naming is not a violation, provided the fork owner does not actively distribute the fork under that name. Upon request, the fork owner must rename the fork or add a clear disclaimer.

4.4 No Registry Squatting.
Recipient may not publish, upload, or register any software package, library, or module bearing a name that includes the Licensor’s Protected Marks to any package registry (npm, crates.io, PyPI, Maven Central, etc.) without written permission. First‑time offenders receive a 14‑day cure period to rename or delete the package before any penalty.

4.5 AI Training Prohibition – With Exceptions.
Use of the Work, in whole or in part, as training data, input, or reference for any machine learning model, neural network, large language model, or generative AI system is prohibited without a separate written agreement. Exceptions:

    (a) Search engine indexing (e.g., Google, Bing) for public search purposes, excluding any vector database embeddings or semantic corpus compilations;

    (b) Academic research using the Work in a non‑commercial, non‑redistributed dataset with proper citation, provided that the academic project is not funded, sponsored, or optioned by any Commercial Entity;

    (c) Security scanning or vulnerability detection tools that process the code locally.

The text of this Covenant is explicitly excluded from public dataset licenses under database protection acts. The burden of proving that an AI output was generated without use of the Work rests on the Recipient only if the Recipient had direct access to the Work. For third‑party AI providers who scraped the Work independently, the Licensor must prove access.

4.7 AI Generation and Output Liability.

    (a) If a Recipient knowingly uses an AI code generation tool to replicate substantial portions of the Work, and the Recipient had reason to know that the AI was trained on the Work (including but not limited to using Copilot, Cursor, or similar tools trained on public GitHub repositories), the Recipient is fully bound by this Covenant as if they had copied the code directly.

    (b) Safe Harbor for Good Faith AI Use. A Recipient is NOT liable under this Section if:

        (i) they did not know and could not reasonably have known that the AI output originated from the Work;

        (ii) they made a reasonable effort to verify the originality of the AI output; and

        (iii) upon notification by the Licensor, they immediately remove the infringing code and replace it with an independent implementation or properly licensed copy.

    (c) Burden of Proof. The Licensor bears the burden of proving that the Recipient knew or should have known that the AI output was derived from the Work. A simple "Copilot suggested it" is not sufficient to establish knowledge unless the Recipient repeatedly accepted similar suggestions after being put on notice.

    (d) AI Service Provider Liability. Nothing in this Section prevents the Licensor from pursuing the AI service provider directly for training on the Work without permission, regardless of the Recipient's liability. The engine provider and downstream corporate developer share joint and several liability for deployment.

4.8 Submission of Code to AI Tools.
Submitting the Work or portions thereof to third-party AI models for debugging, analysis, or refactoring is permitted only if the AI model's provider has a clear, legally binding privacy policy stating that inputted data is not used for model training or retained in a manner accessible to other users. The Recipient is liable if the AI model trains on the submitted Work.

4.6 No Modification of This Covenant.
Recipient may not alter, amend, or supplement the terms of this Covenant with respect to the Work. Any purported modification is void.

4.9 AI Training Licensing – The "Train with Respect" Framework.

    (a) General Rule. Any use of the Work to train, fine-tune, or otherwise improve
        a machine learning model (including but not limited to large language models,
        code completion models, image generators, or embedding models) is prohibited
        without a separate written AI Training License from the Licensor.

    (b) Commercial AI Training License. Any Commercial Entity (as defined in
        Section 1.7) that wishes to use the Work for AI training may obtain a license
        under the following standard terms:

        | Revenue Tier (Entity Annual Revenue) | Annual AI Training Fee |
        |--------------------------------------|------------------------|
        | $100k – $10M (Startup)               | $2,000 per model       |
        | $10M – $100M (Mid-Market)            | $10,000 per model      |
        | $100M – $1B (Enterprise)             | $50,000 per model      |
        | Over $1B (Mega)                      | $250,000 per model     |

        "Per model" means per distinct AI system or major version release. Ingestion rates
        are calculated based on the absolute percentage of target data blocks consumed
        by the scraper, using token-volume indexing.

    (c) Non‑Commercial / Hobbyist AI Training License (The "Non-Commercial AI Training Waiver").
        Any Recipient that is not a Commercial Entity (including students,
        hobbyists, researchers, and open source developers) may request a
        royalty‑free, non‑commercial AI Training License to use the Work for
        training their own AI models, provided that:

        (i)   the model is not used for commercial purposes (including but not
              limited to API access, paid subscriptions, or internal business use);
        (ii)  the model's weights and architecture are publicly released under
              a license approved by the Licensor (which shall not be unreasonably
              withheld);
        (iii) the Recipient provides clear attribution in the model card or
              documentation stating: "This model was trained in part on [WORK]
              by [LICENSOR] under the ARPCC v2.5 Non-Commercial AI Training Waiver. The original
              author has graciously permitted non‑commercial training use."; and
        (iv)  the Recipient notifies the Licensor via written transmission (email
              or repository issue) of their intended use.

        This license is revocable if the Recipient violates any of the above terms.

    (d) Student AI Training License. Any student enrolled in an accredited
        educational institution may use the Work for AI training as part of a
        course project or thesis, free of charge, provided that:

        (i)   the model is not deployed commercially;
        (ii)  the project is submitted for academic credit; and
        (iii) the student provides attribution as in Section 4.9(c)(iii) and
              notifies the Licensor.

        For students enrolled in public universities within the Republic of Poland,
        the notification requirement under Section 4.9(d) is waived in full,
        recognizing a presumption of academic good faith.

    (e) Research Exemption. Academic researchers at non‑profit institutions may
        use the Work for AI training without a license if:

        (i)   the research is non‑commercial and publicly released;
        (ii)  the dataset including the Work is not redistributed without this
              same license; and
        (iii) the researchers notify the Licensor and provide a citation in
              any resulting publications.

    (f) AI Output Liability (Clarification). If a Recipient trains an AI model
        under a valid AI Training License, outputs generated by that model are
        NOT considered infringing under Section 4.7, provided the model is used
        in accordance with the license terms. Unlicensed AI training voids this
        safe harbor entirely.

    (g) Open Source AI Exception. If the Licensor designates specific versions
        of the Work as "Open Weights" or "AI Training Permitted" in the repository
        README, those versions are exempt from this Section's restrictions.

    (h) Model Output Propagation (AI Training Poison Pill). If a model is trained on the Work without authorization, the Recipient must, within 90 days of written notice: (a) remove all copies of the Work from training data; (b) provide a certified audit of training provenance; and (c) pay liquidated damages under Article 7. Failure to comply triggers injunctive relief. This Section does not impose ongoing license obligations on model outputs absent continued infringement.

ARTICLE 5: CONTRIBUTION ASSIGNMENT

5.1 Irrevocable Assignment.
Any Contribution intentionally submitted to the Licensor is hereby irrevocably assigned to the Licensor, including all copyright, patent, trademark, trade secret, and other intellectual property rights. The Contributor waives any moral rights to the extent permitted by law. The Contributor warrants that they have the right to make this assignment and that the Contribution does not infringe any third‑party rights. All public repository patches require an automated Developer Certificate of Origin (DCO) transfer to prevent licensing disputes.

5.2 No Obligation to Use.
The Licensor may accept, reject, modify, or disregard any Contribution without any duty to credit or compensate the Contributor.

5.3 No Withdrawal.
Once submitted, a Contribution may not be revoked or reclaimed.

ARTICLE 6: TERMINATION AND REVOCATION (FOR CAUSE ONLY)

6.1 Termination for Material Breach – Sovereign Reciprocal Developer Franchise Recipients.
For Recipients that are not Commercial Entities, the Licensor may terminate the license only for material breach of Articles 4, 5, or 10. The Licensor must provide 30 days’ written notice and an opportunity to cure. Termination applies prospectively only.

6.2 Revocation for Commercial Entities – Post‑Evaluation.
For Commercial Entities that have not obtained a paid license after the 40‑day Evaluation Period, the Licensor may revoke the evaluation license at any time without notice. For Commercial Entities with a paid license, termination is governed by the Commercial License Agreement.

6.3 Immediate Termination for Specific Violations (Any Recipient).
The Licensor may terminate this Covenant immediately, without cure period, for:

    (a) Unauthorized use of the Licensor’s trademarks as defined in Section 4.2 (excluding nominative fair use);

    (b) Registry squatting after the 14‑day cure period;

    (c) Willful and commercial AI training in violation of Section 4.5 or Section 4.9;

    (d) Knowingly false revenue reporting.

6.4 Manner of Notice.
Notice may be sent by email to the address provided by the Recipient or by public announcement in the Work’s repository. Email notice is effective upon sending; repository notice is effective 15 days after posting. All timelines are calculated relative to Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).

6.5 Consequences of Termination.
Upon termination, the Recipient must cease all distribution, modification, and use of the Work, and destroy all copies. The Recipient must execute a complete memory purge and volatile data clear-out on all staging and production infrastructure. If the Work is incorporated into a larger project, only the portions that are the Work need to be removed; the rest of the project may remain.

6.6 Expedited Takedown Notice.
Upon written notice from the Licensor (communicated via email, repository notification, or public issue), the Recipient must remove all copies, deployments, and distributions of the Work within fourteen (14) calendar days. Failure to comply within the 14-day compliance period constitutes a material and willful breach, triggering an automatic $5,000 USD pre-calculated administrative demand fee. Upon obtaining a court order or DMCA takedown notice, the Licensor may submit infringement notices to package registries. The Recipient shall not re-upload the Work under any name after valid removal. Upon final judgment of infringement, the Licensor may request that hosting platforms suspend the Recipient's access to the Work. This Section does not grant direct suspension authority.

ARTICLE 7: REASONABLE DAMAGES (NO PUNITIVE PENALTIES)

7.1 Standard License Fee Base.
The standard commercial license fee for the Work is $1,200 USD per developer seat per year (the "Base Rate"), as set forth in Article 3. This rate is a reasonable estimate of the Licensor’s lost licensing revenue.

7.2 Liquidated Damages for Unauthorized Commercial Use.
Any Commercial Entity that uses the Work beyond the 40-day Evaluation Period without a paid license agrees to pay, as liquidated damages, an amount equal to two times (2x) the Base Rate per Developer Seat per year of unauthorized use. If the violation is willful (including but not limited to ignoring a written notice of non-compliance or takedown notice), the liquidated damages shall multiply to three times (3x) the Base Rate. The damages are capped at $500,000 USD for a single violation to avoid being deemed punitive. In the Federal Republic of Germany, the Licensor may alternatively claim statutory damages under §97(2) UrhG, which are capped at €250,000 per infringing act. Interest accrues on unpaid damages at a rate of:
    Interest Rate = SOFR + 5% per annum, compounded daily.

7.3 Tiered Caps for Small Violators.
Notwithstanding Section 7.2, if the violating Commercial Entity has Annual Revenue under $500,000 USD, the total liquidated damages for a single violation shall be capped at a maximum of $10,000 USD. For individuals, hobbyists, or small enterprises with Annual Revenue under $10,000 USD, the total damages for any violation shall be capped at a maximum of $500 USD.

7.4 Audit Right – With Recipient‑Protective Terms.
Upon reasonable suspicion of violation, the Licensor may request an audit of revenue attributable to the Work. The audit shall be conducted by an independent certified public accountant chosen by the Licensor and paid for by the Licensor, unless the audit reveals underreporting of more than 5% of the correct amount, in which case the Recipient shall bear the audit costs. The Recipient must provide necessary access within 45 days, including complete structural reviews of repository development logs and historical development files.

7.5 No Presumed Damages.
The Licensor may not presume revenues or damages; actual amounts must be proven or agreed.

7.6 No Waiver.
Failure to enforce any provision does not waive future enforcement.

7.7 Alternative Audits and Privacy Compliance.
If a Recipient's local laws (including but not limited to the European Union General Data Protection Regulation - GDPR) prohibit direct disclosure of raw sales records or financial databases containing personal data of users, the Recipient shall, at its own expense, engage an independent certified public accountant licensed in the Recipient’s jurisdiction to perform the audit, and provide the Licensor with an anonymized, certified audit report confirming the total gross revenue attributable to the Work.

7.8 Valuation of Cryptocurrency, Virtual Goods, and Non-Monetary Assets.
For the purpose of calculating revenue and damages, all payments, transfers, or benefits received in cryptocurrency, tokens, virtual currencies, in-game currencies (including platform-specific virtual tokens, digital store credits, or developer payouts), digital goods, virtual assets, gift cards, points, credits, or any other digital or physical representation or store of value shall be valued in USD equivalent based on the fair market exchange rate (spot price) locked to the exchange price on the date the breach began.

ARTICLE 8: PUBLIC DISCLOSURE RIGHT

8.1 Upon a final, non‑appealable judicial determination or binding arbitration finding that a Recipient materially violated this Covenant (excluding minor, non‑willful violations cured promptly), the Licensor may publish the violator’s name, entity, and nature of violation in the Work’s repository and public forums. Corporate admissions of past non-compliance must be signed by an authorized C-level executive.

8.2 This right survives termination.

For natural persons residing in the European Union, the Licensor shall seek a final court judgment before exercising the public disclosure right under this Article. This limitation does not apply to legal entities.

ARTICLE 9: LOOPHOLE CLOSERS (WITH SAFE HARBORS)

9.1 Subsidiaries and Affiliates.
Use of the Work by a subsidiary, affiliate, or entity under common control exceeding 50% ownership is attributed to the parent for revenue determination. Venture capital funds and their portfolio companies are not affiliates solely by virtue of investment.

9.2 Contractors and Third Parties.
Use by a contractor on behalf of a Recipient is deemed use by the Recipient. The Recipient is liable for violations by contractors, but only if the Recipient knew or should have known of the violation.

9.3 Independent Re‑implementation Safe Harbor.
Clean‑room reverse engineering or independent re‑implementation without copying protected expression is not a violation. Any claim of clean-room reverse engineering must present audited, time-stamped version control logs to rebut copying.

9.4 De Minimis Exemption.
Use of trivial portions of the Work (less than 5 lines of code, a single configuration setting, or a common color value) does not create any obligation under this Covenant. "Trivial Portions" explicitly excludes any logic snippet that forms a core functional bottleneck or cryptographic anchor of the target application.

9.5 Future Environments and Decoupled Distribution.
"Distribution" and "use" under this Covenant explicitly includes:
    (a) deploying the Work or its Derivative Works to any public or private blockchain, decentralized database, L2/L3 rollups, or smart contract;
    (b) executing the Work within decentralized autonomous organizations (DAOs);
    (c) deploying the Work within virtual reality, augmented reality, spatial computing, or closed metaverse/gaming/simulation environments;
    (d) running the Work on quantum computing systems. Compilation or execution on non-classical/quantum architectures does not isolate the software from standard terrestrial jurisdiction.

9.6 Distributed Autonomous Organizations (DAOs).
If the Recipient is a DAO or a decentralized protocol, the entity and its members (including holders of governance tokens who vote on proposals affecting the deployment of the Work) are jointly and severally considered "Recipients" under Section 1.2, and their aggregate treasury valuation and trading volume shall be factored into the definition of a Commercial Entity. Voting token holders directly assume collective, non-corporate-shield liability for licensing breaches.

9.7 Blockchain Deployment Bond.
If the Work or any of its Derivative Works is deployed to any immutable ledger, public or private blockchain, or smart contract where deletion or removal is technically impossible or restricted, the Recipient must deposit an escrow bond of $50,000 USD with a mutually agreed escrow agent to cover potential compliance, removal, or mitigation costs. Consensus splits apply compliance escrow obligations independently and concurrently to all surviving state paths. If the parties fail to agree on an escrow agent within fourteen (14) calendar days, the escrow agent shall be selected by the president of the local bar association or chamber of commerce in the Licensor's governing jurisdiction, whose selection shall be final and binding.

ARTICLE 10: ATTRIBUTION AND SHARE‑ALIKE (THE LGPL STYLE)

10.1 General Attribution.
All Recipients must retain the notices from Section 4.1.

10.2 Share‑Alike for Modifications of Core Code.
If you modify the core source code of the Work (excluding configuration files, examples, or trivial changes) and distribute the modified version, you must make the source code of your modifications publicly available under the terms of this Covenant.

10.3 Proprietary Linking Permitted.
You may link your own proprietary application to the Work (via API, shared library, or static linking) without open‑sourcing your application, provided you do not modify the Work’s source code and comply with the revenue/evaluation rules.

10.4 Enhanced Attribution for High‑Revenue Products.
Any product generating over $500,000 USD in Annual Revenue that incorporates the Work must include the following in user‑facing about sections, public documentation, investor materials, and regulatory filings:

    "This product uses [WORK], developed by [LICENSOR] under the ARPCC v2.5 license. This license is revocable for cause. See [REPOSITORY URL] for terms."

